
[1]scold

   SCOLD, v.i.

   To find fault or rail with rude clamor; to brawl; to utter railing or
   harsh, rude, boisterous rebuke; with at; as, to scold at a servant. A
   scolding tongue, a scolding wife, a scolding husband, a scolding
   master, who can endure?

   Pardon me, 'tis the first time that ever I'm forc'd to scold.

   SCOLD, v.t. To chide with rudeness and boisterous clamor; to rate. [The
     transitive use of this word is of recent origin, at least within my
                                 knowledge.]

                                  SCOLD, n.

   1. A rude, clamorous, foul-mouthed woman.

   Scolds answer foul-mouth'd scolds.

   2. A scolding; a brawl.
